<TEXT>
with exports to the united states and 
other parts of the world sagging south korea is eager to do 
business with the soviet union 
evidence of south korean presence is visible almost as soon as a 
visitor steps off the plane at sheremetyevo airport in moscow the 
1500 baggage carts are emblazoned with signs advertising samsung 
a korean conglomerate 
visitors can rent hyundai automobiles made in south korea buy 
koreanmade fur coats and see koreansponsored quiz shows on 
television they pass billboards advertising korean companies 
placed strategically near the kremlin 
south korea has washing machines refrigerators televisions 
videos sewing machines soap shoes electronics and dozens of 
other moderately priced consumer goods the soviets need south 
koreans hope the soviets have the kinds of advanced technology they 
need and cant get elsewhere 
experts say the ultimate goal is the transfer from moscow to 
seoul of technologies that either the united states and japan will 
nt provide or are too expensive in the west 
among them are core technology in lasers space biotechnology 
nuclear fusion electronics and composite and superhard materials 
with applications that could range from a new kind of automobile 
brake to gene therapy 
does the soviet union have usable high technologies no one 
seems to know the koreans are still looking at the wares 
searching for nuggets a western expert said 
analyst kim byongkuk said the cardinal inducement for 
koreansoviet economic cooperation stems from the fact that both 
nations are in a position to offer what the other party needs 
most 
president roh taewoo visited moscow two weeks ago less than 
three months after the governments established normal relations he 
said his summit talks with mikhail s gorbachev heralded a new era 
of mutual prosperity 
the soviet union has advanced science and technology we need 
and we can provide consumer goods and facilities roh said 
north korea assailed the visit and indirectly criticized its 
soviet allies but with little effect 
a day after roh returned the science and technology ministry 
announced that 281 soviet technologies were expected to be 
transferred for commercial application including those for nuclear 
fusion and fast breeder reactors 
in return south korea is to provide production technology for 
consumer goods 
the bank of korea said 91 million had been approved for 
investment by middecember in january south korea is expected to 
complete an economic cooperation and loan package said to total 3 
billion 
trade between the two countries doubled in 1989 to 600 million 
it is expected to exceed 1 billion in 1990 and south korean 
officials have predicted levels of up to 10 billion within five 
years 
after years of selling copycat items at low prices because of 
low wages the south koreans are trying to catch up 
technologically to compete in an atmosphere of rising labor and 
production costs they need to make more advanced products of 
higher quality 
as if to emphasize the point the last stop roh made in the 
soviet union was the ioffe physicotechnical institute in leningrad 
japan is making a lot of money by dominating the worlds 
semiconductor market he was quoted as saying if we combine 
soviet advanced technology and south koreas application know how 
we can split the profit 
many south koreans feel the soviets are using this country as 
bait to lure a bigger fish japan into committing billions of 
dollars to longrange development of soviet natural resources 
high technology is especially urgent for south korea said 
dr rhee sangwoo a specialist in public policy but for japan 
its meaningless they dont need soviet high technology south 
korea is bait to fish japan 
japan has held off because of a territorial dispute over a group 
of islands and because it views investment in the soviet union as 
risky observers feel development of close commercial relations 
between moscow and seoul will make japanese businessmen uneasy and 
more susceptible to soviet advances 
among the technologies south korea wants most are those for high 
definition television which displays pictures that are stunning in 
color and detail 
the soviet union is said to possess the technology but has been 
unable to build and market it high definition television already 
is a multibilliondollar industry in japan and is beginning to 
catch on in the united states 
daewoo corp parent company of the giant daewoo group 
conglomerate recently signed two jointventure contracts with the 
soviets with the aim of commercializing new soviet technologies 
the contracts are with the ioffe institute and the soviet 
ministry of atomic energy and industry the technologies include 
those applicable to high definition television new methods to cast 
aluminum nuclear membranes for making work spaces germfree and 
technology for treating industrial waste daewoo said 
