<TEXT>
tis the night before christmas and all 
through the house and senate lots of creatures are stirring 
especially mice 
the capitol is a building alive 
although the exact number is a national secret or it would be 
if it could be determined there is a battalion of mice living in 
the historic structure 
occasionally they make themselves known including memorable 
sightings on the house floor and in speaker thomas foleys old 
office perhaps when no one is around but the guards they frolic 
openly 
but beyond the squeaks of its diminutive yearround residents 
the capitol itself speaks 
sometimes it speaks of fear 
metal detectors and xray machines erected at nearly every 
entrance tell of a decade of increasing unease about terrorism 
hidden cameras watch the corridors 
a careful observer can rap steel inserts in the seatbacks of the 
house chamber and find a patch in the republican leaders desk 
where a bullet from a puerto rican nationalists gun penetrated 
four decades ago 
on the senate side a beefedup wall stands behind the ohio 
clock which was restored after a 1983 bomb explosion shattered its 
delicate wooden housing 
sometimes it speaks of vanity 
for example lawmakers since world war ii have taken to naming 
the rooms after themselves 
historical greats such as daniel webster and henry clay command 
no territory beyond their statues but speaker foley holds meetings 
in the thomas p oneill room named after the massachusetts 
democrat and former speaker 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine works in a 
suite named after his predecessor sen robert c byrd dwva and 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan labors in the howard baker 
rooms named for his predecessor 
the rush for recognition in the senate has so gobbled up real 
estate that some worry there may soon be no good rooms left to 
name already a christmas eve visitor would find telephone booths 
in the democratic cloakroom named for senior senators 
not only the elected officials have egos architect of the 
capitol george white had his portrait added to the collection 
painted on the arched ceilings in the house wing 
the building on the hill also speaks of power 
a sign on the door tells visitors that the house document room 
is no longer adjacent to beautiful statuary hall the repository of 
bills and reports has been moved out of the building so that 
speaker foley can add to his everexpanding kingdom 
nameplates on doors throughout the building indicate the offices 
of the most powerful and senior chairman names like rostenkowski 
whitten and byrd 
doors with no names also tell tales to those who know many are 
senators hideaways private retreats only steps from the senate 
floor where lawmakers can work undisturbed hold secret meetings or 
just catch a nap during a late session 
all around the building speaks of age and decay 
scaffolds abound during the congressional recess as expert 
plasterers and painters repair the wounds time and nature have 
inflicted on the structure 
and at the top of the dome the statue freedom is crying for its 
upcoming restoration after a century of rain wind and lightning 
and the capitol speaks of hope both whimsical and not 
the shoes of the statue of will rogers shine from people 
touching them for luck i do it more in election years says 
rep mike snyder dokla 
nearby in the rotunda among the grandiose paintings and 
statuary is a plain black and white flag with a symbol of a 
captive soldier and the letters powmia 
it always speaks its just easier to hear during the holidays 
