<TEXT>
richard kimball envisions a future in which 
voters reject television campaign commercials and select national 
leaders as they would prospective employees by reviewing their 
resumes 
he has taken a leave from his job to try to make those resumes 
and more available to voters by telephone in 1992 on every 
candidate running for national office from every state 
the people in congress are the hired help said kimball 
were saying if you the voter are the employer what do you 
need to know 
kimball a political science teacher and former arizona state 
senator is directing the center for national independence in 
politics a nonprofit organization whose honorary cochairmen are 
former presidents gerald ford and jimmy carter 
kimball says that by 1992 the center will offer a telephone 
number providing voters 
basic personal information on each candidate 
names of people and organizations who have contributed to the 
campaign 
ratings of the candidate by special interest groups ranging 
from the american conservative union to the american civil 
liberties union 
kimball worked briefly many years ago in the washington offices 
of sen patrick moynihan dny and rep morris udall dariz 
after serving in the arizona senate for four years and as 
chairman of the arizona corporation commission which regulates 
utilities kimball ran for the us senate in 1986 but lost to 
sen john mccain a republican 
melodee jackson arizona democratic party executive director 
said some people questioned kimballs decision to run a longshot 
campaign against mccain when he had a secure and successful career 
with the regulatory commission 
he probably would have been reelected to the commission for 
as long as he wanted to run she said 
kimball is passionate about politics and unconventional in that 
he doesnt hold up his finger to see which way the wind is 
blowing before he takes a position jackson said 
kimball said his senate race against the wellfinanced mccain 
campaign showed him the importance of television in modern 
elections but the imagemaking quality of tv commercials sickened 
him 
the ads used nowadays are disastrous in a democracy said 
kimball how can you possibly expect people to govern themselves 
if what is put before them is not a discussion of public policy 
people cannot deal with the manipulation theyre being buried 
by meaningless information 
he said campaign finance laws can be changed but voters wont 
be better off if the money available is still used to build images 
irrelevant to issues facing the country 
the idea for the telephone service came while kimball was 
talking to former sen william proxmire dwis who campaigned for 
him in 1986 and former sen barry goldwater rariz who is a 
lifelong acquaintance 
the three of them contacted other political figures to serve on 
the centers board of directors the 35member board is equally 
divided among democrats and republicans and includes others 
unaffiliated with a party 
last election the center experimented with its concept in 
nebraska and north carolina 
we got about 6000 calls said kimball since the center did 
no paid advertising the calls were generated by news stories and 
word of mouth after one press conference 
when people called the 800number they got an operator with 
access to a computer holding the information on each candidate 
kimball said about 50 percent of the callers wanted voting 
record ratings and 25 percent sought campaign finance information 
but operators also got calls seeking a range of biographical 
details 
kimball says the center needs at least 500000 to run a 
nationwide telephone service using tollfree numbers but he said a 
selffinancing 900number system would be used if sufficient funds 
arent raised it would cost 3 a call 
seed money for the project which operated on a budget of 
290000 last year came from 35 memberships obtained through 
direct mail solicitations and a total of about 100000 from five 
foundations carnegie deer creek foundation mary reynolds 
babcock benton foundation and arca 
the center is based in tucson ariz and staffed predominantly 
by volunteers including kimball the board members are unpaid and 
include rep jim leach riowa peggy lampl former president of 
the league of women voters kenneth adelman former head of the 
us arms control and disarmament agency 1984 democratic vice 
presidential nominee geraldine ferraro sen david boren dokla 
john echohawk head native americans rights fund former sen 
george mcgovern dsd and irene natividad former president of 
the national womens political caucus 
</TEXT>
