<TEXT>
if people living in small towns and on small 
farms are to be helped a first step must be the formation of a 
national policy on rural development a presidential panel has 
concluded 
the national commission on agriculture and rural development 
policy said in a report sent to president bush that the 1980s 
were much harder on many rural areas than on their urban 
counterparts 
it cited economic crises in the agricultural and energy sectors 
along with tough new foreign competition in manufacturing and 
the relative disadvantage rural people have in obtaining adequate 
affordable health care education and other vital services 
another factor noted by the report is the physical and social 
isolation that separate rural america from the economic activity 
of city life 
the 15member commission was appointed for two years by 
president reagan it was authorized by the 1985 farm law which is 
now expiring 
in its first report a year ago the commission examined 
agricultural policy issues and called for a more flexible 
marketoriented farm policy that would leave it up to farmers to 
decide what crops to plant but still provide a safety net for 
hard times 
the 1990 farm law which runs for five years after the current 
one expires provided some of that flexibility in its commodity 
programs 
in its final report the commission focused on rural development 
and some of the things local people and their governments ought to 
be doing and thinking about 
no massive federal aid package was called for rather the 
commission felt there are many problems in rural america and 
rural americans are dealing with them for their fate is in their 
own hands 
still it said the federal government has a critical support 
role to play through many channels including the use of existing 
programs to help people and communities financially 
when and if a rural development policy is formulated it will 
be done in a different context from that of the past the report 
said there is currently no defined rural development policy 
instead there exists a loose collection of individual programs 
those partly resulted the report said from the division among 
various federal agencies and among the federal state and local 
governments as to who had the responsibility for rural development 
the federal government no longer plays the lead role nor do 
we expect it to the commission reported 
as many others have noted in recent years the report made it 
clear again that the problems of rural america are not homogeneous 
nor should they be solely equated with agriculture 
farming is still a vital part of the rural economy the 
report said however it directly employs less than 10 percent of 
the rural work force mining manufacturing tourism services and 
government are also important industries in the rural economy 
thus the report added neither farm policy nor any other 
singleissue policy can sufficiently address the needs of rural 
america 
the commission said the first step toward helping rural 
america is to articulate the goals for rural development policy 
which it said are not solely economic in nature 
three principles were listed by the commission as guides for 
rural development 
rural areas and people must be economically selfreliant in a 
highly competitive marketoriented world economy selfreliance is 
critical if the rural economy is to generate better jobs and income 
for its residents 
rural areas and people must be able to adapt the world economy 
has changed rapidly in recent years economic change is predicted 
to become even more rapid as a result rural areas must develop 
the ability to respond rapidly and effectively to changing market 
conditions 
the rural physical and cultural environment should be 
protected the physical environment in rural areas and the cultural 
heritage of rural people are valuable elements of national life and 
livelihood enjoyed by rural and urban residents alike and deserve 
protection 
</TEXT>
