<TEXT>
after 168 years clement moores holiday poem 
the night before christmas is solid as gold 
but another of his creations stately st peters episcopal 
church for which he donated the land and design is falling 
apart 
the churchs patched sagging roof probably couldnt support a 
sleigh let alone eight tiny reindeer and its back wall bulges 
like santas belly 
theres a nice pile of stones out in the garden and theyve 
all fallen out of the tower said ronald kastner who heads a 
campaign to raise 3 million to repair the new york city landmark 
the churchs 130foot bell tower is held together by steel 
cables and masked by scaffolding the towers fourfaced clock is 
still and many of its stones have fallen and damaged the roof of 
the nave windows that once boasted tiffanystyle stained glass are 
boarded up 
if we dont get the money kastner said the tower will 
fall onto the roof and the roof will collapse and the church will 
close 
the episcopal diocese of new york gave the congregation 500000 
for repairs but st peters must raise the needed 3 million more 
tself 
the church is just one of clement clarke moores many 
accomplishments born in 1779 he grew up on what was then his 
familys rural estate the area is now part of manhattans bustling 
chelsea neighborhood 
in 1817 moore donated the church property for the general 
theological seminary where he was a distinguished biblical scholar 
for three decades but he is remembered for an account of a visit 
from st nicholas also known as the night before christmas 
he is said to have written the poem during a sleigh ride home 
from greenwich village just before christmas 1822 and to have read 
it later to his six children the piece was published a year later 
in the troy sentinel and helped create st nicks image as a 
jolly old elf who looked more like a peddler than a childrens 
saint 
but even as moores composition was rising to fame its pastoral 
setting was disappearing in the 1820s chelsea was a 
twostagecoach trip from what was then the city and is now lower 
manhattan but urbanites were moving steadily north to escape 
disease and congestion 
around 1830 moore decided to develop his farm called chelsea 
as a planned residential suburb he sold the land in lots but 
attached restrictions no alleys stables or factories and no 
building within 10 feet of the sidewalk moore the developer 
transformed the landscape 
moore the poet said historian stephen nissenbaum helped 
transform the nations most widely observed holiday from a big 
public occasion of rowdiness that lasted a month into a domestic 
and private event within the family 
st peters with its tower and massively buttressed fieldstone 
walls became a focal point of the new neighborhood upon its 
completion in 1838 moore persuaded the congregation to accept a 
neogothic design inspired by his visits to english churches 
by 1900 st peters had about 500 parishioners but membership 
fell off as the building declined it was closed temporarily in 
1941 because of leaks in the roof 
over the years water continued to seep into the building 
loosening the mortar that held its stones and weakening the roofs 
wooden framing 
when the rev wray mackay took over as vicar the church 
averaged 10 people at sunday services but mackay expanded the 
congregation by increasing its services including an aids 
ministry a food pantry a program for the areas welfare hotel 
residents and seasonal clothing drives the church now has about 
200 members 
moore died in 1863 and is buried 130 blocks uptown at trinity 
cemetery there every christmas eve carolers gather to sing the 
praises of the citys most illustrious theologian poet developer 
and architect 
