<TEXT>
the alarm first sounded three years ago 
when one of brandeis universitys dining halls started serving pork 
and shellfish 
now the departure of the schools president has heightened 
debate over the schools jewish identity 
one jewish scholar argues that the changes made by president 
evelyn handler symbolized something not only about the school but 
about choices jews have to make in american society 
brandeis university has been struggling with what could be 
seen in a complex way as this temptation to assimilate gordon 
fellman an associate professor of sociology wrote in the 
novemberdecember edition of tikkun a liberal jewish publication 
based in oakland calif 
founded in 1948 the year israel became a state brandeis was 
named after justice louis d brandeis the first jew on the us 
supreme court the schools jewish founders wanted it to be 
nonsectarian like harvard and notre dame 
the school today has an enrollment of 3600 and an endowment of 
150 million in recent years the student body was estimated to be 
65 percent jewish a school spokesman said he didnt know what that 
percentage is now 
handler became the universitys fifth president in 1983 and 
encountered criticism in 1987 over changes in the dining hall and 
the schools logo 
the menu change officially was billed as internationalizing the 
cuisine fellman said brandeis had always maintained one dining 
hall for kosher students and another hall for others but while the 
nonkosher hall would serve milk with meat violating strict jewish 
dietary laws it did not serve meat considered impure in the jewish 
tradition until 1987 
at about the same time brandeis removed the hebrew word for 
truth from the schools logo fellman said and the university 
calendar dropped references to jewish holidays 
amid a campus outcry the logo and holiday references have been 
restored 
handler announced in june that she would resign at the end of 
this school year shes now on sabbatical 
she has refused to discuss her decision to step down im not 
prepared to talk to you over the telephone or any other place 
she said when asked for an interview 
david rosen a university spokesman said members of the 
brandeis community blew changes in the dining hall and the school 
logo out of proportion 
