you charter the number of ships that we charter its going to have 
an effect on the price 
its a question of supply and demand said robert w 
kesteloot a shipping consultant in reston va who retired in 
1986 after six years as the navys director of strategic sealift 
the shippers run a great risk if they accept cargo going out 
there kesteloot said 
he said that if shippers displace other cargo to take on the 
military loads they may not get the other customers back after the 
crisis in the gulf is over 
kesteloot said he knew of charter ships that were now bringing 
in more than 50 percent more than they could demand six months ago 
he said container rates have also risen sharply 
the new york times in an article published today said the navy 
has been paying nearly 8000 for each standard 40by8by 8 
12foot steel container used to send supplies to the gulf from the 
east coast the times said this is twice what some commercial 
shippers now pay 
