<TEXT>
the chapel is simple and the pews are 
planks propped on stones after nearly 26 years in jail in a 
country he calls the hell of the world a christmas dream has 
come true for the leader of albanias roman catholics 
for the first time since 1967 when albania became the only 
communist state to outlaw religion simon jubani and thousands of 
his flock can gather to celebrate the birth of jesus 
greek orthodox believers in southern albania have opened three 
churches 
moslems are repairing some of the few mosques that survived 
state efforts to wipe out religion moslems make up about 70 
percent of albanian believers another 20 percent are orthodox and 
10 percent are catholic 
the miraculous change in believers fortunes came in november 
after the ruling communists lifted the ban on religion as part of 
limited reforms in the isolated backward land of 33 million 
people 
young people in shkodra who had dared to preserve their catholic 
faith took over this small chapel in a rundown cemetery 
since nov 4 jubani said mass has been celebrated every day 
from 1000 to 2000 people flock daily to the chapel on the city 
boulevard named for the father of stalinist albania enver hoxha 
jubani was jailed eight times for nearly 26 years on charges of 
propagandizing against the atheist communism brutally imposed by 
hoxha 
he was surprised when the government freed him in april 1989 
and he began celebrating mass in secret in his home 
without the changes wrought in the communist world by soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev jubani said he would have served 
out the remaining 20 years of his last sentence 
asked how he survived jails in which he said at least 100 roman 
catholic priests had died jubani said he was sustained by faith in 
the traditional catholicism of shkodra 
as byzantine power could not do anything to us for 900 years 
and ottoman power could not do anything for 500 years so the 
communists also could do nothing to us the 63yearold priest 
said with a smile shkodra he said is like an oasis in the 
albanian desert 
shkodra is reputedly one of europes oldest cities and was for 
centuries a center of catholicism under hoxha it decayed as funds 
flowed south to his hometown of gjirokaster near the greek border 
reported unrest in shkodra earlier this year and perhaps the 
influence of hoxhas successor ramiz alia a shkodra native have 
led the communists to pay more attention to albanias third city of 
about 80000 
but that was not sufficient to quell an explosion of popular 
anger this month after alia announced that other political parties 
would be permitted after 46 years of oneparty rule 
a hoxha statue was blown up local communist headquarters and 
the radio station vandalized and hundreds of windows smashed before 
security forces intervened 
we are living in political chaos said jubani referring to 
the turmoil and hatred that could be unleashed by the communists 
reforms 
his chapel is a haven of humanity and believers have given it 
the spirit of christmas 
one carefully painted a wooden altarpiece another brought 
virgin mary portraits and other artifacts jubani said were hidden 
from the communists by the religious spirit always in our 
hearts 
other believers proudly showed a nativity scene 
albania is the hell of the world jubani said referring to 
the communist rule of terror that he said extended even to pulling 
