maine consumers will become the nations 
busiest recyclers next monday when the states bottle deposit law 
is expanded to include nearly all nondairy beverage containers 
even though maine residents will have to rinse save and return 
more bottles and cans than ever they seem to be taking the new law 
in stride 
it will probably be more of a nuisance in a sense said 
charlene haney of caribou i suppose once you get used to it it 
will be all right 
mrs haney said the need to reduce the mountains of throwaways 
filling landfills more than justifies the extra burden i 
understand why theyre doing this she said 
for more than a decade maine residents have been paying 
deposits on beer and soda containers under a law designed to reduce 
litter but with the advent of the solid waste crisis the law took 
on new meaning 
a comprehensive solid waste law expanded the bottle law to 
include liquor bottles as of jan 1 1990 and wine bottles on 
sept 1 1990 aseptic containers or juice boxes were banned 
in maine as of september 
as of dec 31 the bottle law will include all noncarbonated 
juice containers holding a gallon or less 
deposits are 5 cents except on liquor and wine bottles which 
carry a 15cent deposit 
excluded are containers for milk and other dairy products 
cider cough syrup sauces baby formula soup and vinegar 
maines new law considered the nations most expansive will 
increase by as much as 50 percent the 600 million tons of beverage 
containers already in the recycling stream according to denise 
lord of the maine waste management agency 
were geared up for it said gary hilliard president of 
returnable services inc whose company accepts pays refunds and 
sorts used bottles and cans before taking them to centers that 
recycle plastic metal and glass 
hilliard added space to his augusta warehouse by tearing out 
closets and using overhead room but he acknowledges that he may 
have to build an addition 
besides adding to the volume of containers being recycled and 
kept out of dumps maines law is also creating a new line of 
business for companies such as hilliards 
juice makers are hiring those companies to pick up their brands 
containers from restaurants and other retailers and take them to 
recycling centers beer and soda manufacturers in maine generally 
do that themselves 
ms lord said the law also has social benefits were seeing a 
real increase in the number of community organizations using bottle 
drives as fundraisers 
other states are watching carefully to see how maines law works 
out said pat franklin of the national container recycling 
coalition a washington dcbased advocacy group various 
components of maines law have been adopted in other states but 
maines law is the most comprehensive she said 
a few kinks in the law remain to be worked out its not clear 
for example whether grocers or companies hired to pick up empties 
must sort containers by manufacturer 
but that wont delay the new law even though a ruling by the 
state isnt expected until january said john joyce of the maine 
grocers association 
the law is expected to cause some manufacturers to pull products 
that sell poorly in maine said joyce other products may disappear 
briefly if manufacturers decide not to use temporary stickers while 
cans and bottles are being redesigned with marks showing they are 
returnable 
