<TEXT>
after an emotional vote to keep socialist in 
the countrys name the soviet congress on monday endorsed the 
concept of a new union treaty to keep the nation from breaking 
apart 
the national parliament also voted to require every republic to 
hold a referendum asking its residents whether they want to remain 
in a restructured union 
lawmakers later approved president mikhail s gorbachevs 
proposal for a national referendum to decide whether to scrap 
communist ideology and allow private ownership of land 
the 2250member congress of peoples deputies charged the 
supreme soviet the smaller standing legislature which it elects 
to draft the precise wording of both referenda and set dates for 
them 
officials said votes on the private property referendum would be 
counted separately in each republic but it was unclear whether a 
few republics could permit private property if the majority did 
not 
the legislature of the republic of russia which encompasses 
threequarters of the soviet land mass already has approved 
private property boris yeltsin russias president and gorbachevs 
main political rival has said there is no need for a referendum 
alexander zhuravlev a deputy from the byelorussian capital of 
minsk set off hisses and a raucous debate by suggesting the soviet 
union rename itself simply russia 
a legislative committee had proposed changing the countrys name 
from the union of soviet socialist republics to the union of 
sovereign soviet republics to reflect the republics growing 
autonomy 
urging the congress to take a holy act the day before 
christmas zhuravlev said our fatherland is russian and so i 
propose that we call ourselves as we did in the past russia 
leningrad mayor anatoly sobchak proposed instead that the 
congress adopt the name favored by the late nobel prize winning 
dissident andrei sakharov the union of soviet republics of 
europe and asia 
other delegates chipped in with union of soviet republics 
and the treaty between russia and its colonies 
congress chairman anatoly lukyanov cut off the heated debate 
telling the deputies to put your emotions back in your pockets 
the congress then voted 1365189 with 170 abstentions to retain 
the name union of soviet socialist republics 
immediately after the vote a delegate who did not identify 
himself rose to object that it was meaningless 
we have voted for socialism but what kind of socialism he 
said 
stalinist socialism brezhnevtype socialism rationcard 
socialism or swedish socialism no matter what we name our 
country we still need to define its economic system 
the deputies paid no heed to his criticism and proceeded to 
endorse the general concept of a new union treaty proposed by 
gorbachev to hold the independenceminded republics together in a 
loose federation 
the congress vote of 149188 with 141 abstentions is not 
binding the treaty which would replace the 1922 document that 
formally created the soviet union must be adopted by the 
legislatures of the 15 republics 
in the past year all 15 republics have declared some form of 
political independence or economic autonomy in which their laws 
take precedence over national ones 
in the referendum envisioned by the congress citizens across 
the country will vote on the general question of whether their 
republics should stay in the soviet union and not on a specific 
treaty 
republics that vote not to remain in the soviet union still 
would not gain immediate independence gorbachev has insisted they 
follow a complicated secession law approved last spring that 
includes a waiting period of up to five years 
parliaments of several republics including georgia lithuania 
latvia estonia and armenia have said they will not sign a new 
union treaty 
gorbachevs proposed draft would give more economic autonomy to 
the republics while retaining a powerful central government in 
moscow with control over foreign policy banking taxation 
defense transportation and communications 
the congress also approved a resolution on the state of the 
union that included a vaguely worded nonbinding endorsement of 
gorbachevs proposed changes in the structure of government 
later in the week the lawmakers are expected to consider 
specific changes and constitutional amendments needed to put them 
into effect mondays resolution did not spell out gorbachevs 
proposals which include a national security council a vice 
presidency and a federation council made up of leaders of the 
republics 
