rushdie has been in hiding under police guard since february 
1989 when iranian leader ayatollah ruhollah khomeini said the 
writer deserved death as a blasphemer iran offered a 1 million 
bounty for rushdies death 
this is the way we hope that will earn rushdies release from 
his predicament this is how we intend to make him a free man 
said elessawy 
elessawy argued as he has in the past that rushdie could not 
be sentenced to death as an apostate because he was not a believing 
moslem 
now that rushdie has embraced the faith by declaring there is 
no god but allah and that mohammed is his last prophet elessawy 
said that the slate is wiped clean 
elessawy characterized rushdie as a convert and quoted the 
author as saying there is no difference between rushdie and 
islam 
other british moslems who have been prominent in the controversy 
demanded more from rushdie 
it puzzles me that he hasnt gone far enough to remove the 
hardback if thats the intention the moslem community has been 
suffering for a long time said sher azam of the council for 
mosques in bradford where the book had been publicly burned 
until the book is completely removed our campaign goes on 
azam said 
iqbal sacranie joint convener of the uk committee on islamic 
affairs said rushdies statement was a positive step however 
it seems to us that the most appropriate course of action is 
the withdrawal from circulation of this blasphemous book 
rushdie recently has come out of hiding for a television 
interview and on dec 5 he appeared at a london bookshop to sign 
copies of his latest book haroun and the sea of stories 
iran severed diplomatic relations with britain over the 
satanic verses but ties were restored in october after an 
18month break on dec 9 however iranian minister of culture 
mohammad khatami said the death sentence against rushdie could not 
be revoked 
elessawy said he met with rushdie on friday in a secure 
location 
he said they were joined at the meeting by dr mohammed ali 
mahgoub an egyptian government official who heads the supreme 
council of scholars of islamic affairs youssef ahmed el sharkawy 
2nd secretary at the egyptian embassy and two clergy from the 
regents park mosque in london 
according to elessawy rushdie made four points in the 
statement 
1 to witness that there is no god but allah and that 
mohammed is his last prophet 
2 to declare that i do not agree with any statement in my 
novel the satanic verses uttered by any of the characters who 
insults the prophet mohammed or casts aspersions upon islam or 
upon the authenticity of the holy koran or who rejects the 
divinity of allah 
3 i undertake not to publish the paperback edition of the 
satanic verses or to permit any further agreement for translations 
into other languages while any risk of further offense exists 
4 i will continue to work for a better understanding of islam 
in the world as i have always attempted to do in the past 
the satanic verses has sold more than 1 million copies in 
english almost threequarters of those in the united states and 
was on the sunday times of londons bestseller list for nearly a 
year it has been translated into 15 languages and banned in more 
than 20 countries 
rushdie born in bombay and now a naturalized british citizen 
has been in hiding since feb 14 1989 
moslems worldwide objected to rushdies use of the names of the 
prophet mohammeds wives for the prostitutes in his novel and the 
implication that mohammed wrote the koran islams holy book 
instead of receiving it from god 
in september 1989 a trade survey found booksellers in england 
divided on the question of stocking any paperback edition forty 
percent said they would not handle it 44 percent said they would 
according to publishing news 
a london newspaper the observer reported last year that viking 
penguin had decided to publish the paperback in 1990 but the 
company never made any announcement 
in january the company said it was unlikely to announce its 
plans in advance because of the security implications 
</TEXT>
