<DOCNO> AP901224-0098 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the state supreme court on monday stripped 
a prosecutionsponsored crime initiative of its most ambitious 
provision a narrowing of many constitutional rights in criminal 
cases 
the court ruled unanimously that a portion of proposition 115 
approved by state voters last june made such a fundamental change 
in the structure of california government that it amounted to a 
revision of the state constitution which cannot be done by 
initiative 
the court upheld the rest of the measure on a 61 vote 
dubbed the speedy trial initiative by sponsors proposition 115 
contained numerous changes aimed at shortening court proceedings in 
criminal cases including restrictions on pretrial hearings 
continuances and questioning of prospective jurors it also 
requires defense lawyers to disclose evidence to prosecutors before 
trial 
one provision required state courts in criminal cases to follow 
us supreme court rulings in applying a long list of 
constitutional rights many of which have been interpreted by state 
courts as giving broader protection for defendants than federal 
rulings 
the court in an opinion by chief justice malcolm lucas 
declared the constitutional changes to be a revision rather 
than a valid constitutional amendment a revision can be submitted 
to voters only by the legislature or a constitutional convention 
california courts would lose power to interpret fundamental 
rights and ultimate protection of criminal defendants from 
deprivation of their constitutional rights would be left in the 
care of the united states supreme court lucas wrote 
the ruling keeps california at the forefront of the movement 
among state supreme courts across the country to give independent 
meaning to their state constitutions said gerald uelmen dean of 
the university of santa clara law school one of three lawyers who 
filed suit against proposition 115 
chief assistant attorney general richard iglehart whose office 
defended the measure said procedural changes remaining in the 
measure such as new time limits on hearings and trialsetting and 
the conduct of preliminary hearings are already quickening the 
pace of criminal cases around the state 
under proposition 115 preliminary hearings the 
sometimeslengthy sessions to determine whether a defendant should 
be held for trial are abbreviated the hearings are eliminated 
when a grand jury issues an indictment 
the measure also requires judges rather than lawyers to question 
prospective jurors requires pretrial disclosures of evidence by 
the defense formerly required only of the prosecutor requires 
defense lawyers to be prepared for trial in 60 days and makes it 
harder for the defense to get separate trials for multiple crimes 
the measure also allows 16yearolds convicted of capital murder 
to be sentenced to life without parole establishes penalties for a 
newly defined crime of torture and expands the death penalty 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

