a judge ordered the federal government 
monday to pay more than 700000 to survivors of two pilots killed 
in a midair collision over a suburb in 1987 
survivors of the four pilots killed in the jan 15 1987 
collision two in each aircraft sued the federal government 
claiming negligence on the part of air traffic controllers at salt 
lake international airport the pilots were among 10 people killed 
in the accident 
us district judge thomas greene ruled that controllers were 51 
percent responsible for the crash and that the government should 
pay damages to the families of chester baker and paul lietz pilots 
of the smaller private plane 
controllers are federal employees 
greene awarded the baker family 387000 and the lietz family 
377000 the survivors of the skywest pilots settled with the 
government for an undisclosed amount in october 
in a 37page ruling greene said baker and lietz were partially 
responsible because they had entered restricted airspace moments 
before the crash 
the judge also concluded the controller in charge of a skywest 
metroliner which was on its final approach into the airport 
should have seen the smaller plane on the radar scope and alerted 
the metroliner 
the us attorneys office was closed monday and officials could 
not be reached for comment 
