<DOCNO> AP901224-0123 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
dec 1723 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the philadelphia inquirer apologized 
publicly for an editorial that had been attacked as racist because 
it linked a new contraceptive to efforts to reverse poverty 
the apology was contained in an editorial in the newspapers 
dec 23 edition 
the newspaper took the unusual step in response to criticism of 
a dec 12 editorial that suggested the contraceptive norplant 
recently approved by the federal government could help solve the 
problem of poverty among blacks 
the earlier norplant editorial undercut our credibility and 
our efforts to be a thoughtful responsible and compassionate voice 
on the complex issues of poverty the newspaper said we 
apologize to those we hurt and offended 
the apology said the newspapers own reporters editors and 
editorial board members were among those incensed by the original 
editorial it was printed alongside five letters to the editor 
containing both praise and criticism 
the original editorial discussed two stories in the previous 
days newspaper one was about norplant which prevents pregnancy 
through implants of tiny rods under the skin and stays effective 
for years and the other was about a research finding that nearly 
half of black children live in poverty and the situation is growing 
worse 
 
here is the text of the editorial headlined an apology and 
subtitled the editorial on norplant and poverty was misguided 
and wrongheaded 
 
its rare that we regret publishing an editorial from almost the 
moment it appears in print and its rarer still that we feel the 
need to apologize to our readers for a misguided and wrongheaded 
editorial opinion but such is the case with the editorial that 
appeared in this space on dec 12 entitled norplant and 
poverty great pain anger and controversy have resulted from 
that editorial and we deeply regret our decision to print it 
among the people who were incensed by the editorial were many of 
the inquirers own reporters editors and members of the editorial 
board in the days since it appeared we have been doing a lot of 
listening and soulsearching 
we realize now that we hastily and foolishly juxtaposed two news 
items that appeared in the inquirer the previous day federal 
approval of the longterm contraceptive norplant and the release of 
a research groups report that said nearly half of black children 
are living in poverty and that the situation is getting worse with 
time the editorial posed the question of whether encouraging women 
who are on welfare to use norplant could help reverse this bleak 
trend 
where did we go wrong lets begin with the headline which 
asked whether contraception could reduce the underclass and 
thus aroused peoples fears of something far worse than promoting 
birth control later we used the word eugenics as a way of 
explaining what we didnt mean but it only inflamed matters more 
most fundamentally in linking the issues of race and 
contraception we left too many people with the impression that our 
cure for poverty was to reduce the number of black people although 
that certainly was not what we meant to suggest the fact that so 
many people interpreted it that way is a clear indication that the 
editorial was fatally flawed therefore we failed in our effort to 
provoke thoughtful discussion on the issue of birth control and 
poverty 
its true that many single young women lessen their chances of 
escaping poverty by having children too early in life but itsalso true 
that the very hopelessness of their circumstances often 
underlies the decision not to postpone childbearing creating hope 
where none now exists must be the main tenet of any effective war 
on poverty 
in the previous editorial we said that women on welfare should 
be encouraged but not compelled to use norplant we suggested 
incentives such as an additional benefit of some kind our critics 
countered that to dangle cash or some other benefit in front of a 
desperately poor woman is tantamount to coercion theyre right 
we still believe that this new form of reliable birth control 
which is likely to have wide appeal to middleclass women should 
be equally available to poor women who want to use it but we also 
realize and should have been even clearer about it that this 
has to be a matter of personal choice we dont seek to limit the 
options of poor women but to empower them 
we remain committed to a whole host of strategies for reducing 
poverty from better schools to job training to radical welfare 
reform we think education about birth control is important and if 
norplant lives up to its advance billing it could be helpful to 
many women 
and we wish we had said it that way to begin with the earlier 
norplant editorial undercut our credibility and our efforts to be a 
thoughtful responsible and compassionate voice on the complex 
issues of poverty we apologize to those we hurt and offended 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
