<TEXT>
the daily news accused its striking unions of 
violating federal labor law by using a campaign of violence 
against the newspapers dealers and advertisers 
the allegations were contained in a lawsuit filed dec 17 the 
second filed by the news against the unions in us district court 
in manhattan since the strike began oct 25 
the first lawsuit was brought under the civil racketeering 
statute and accused the nine striking unions of coordinating a 
violent conspiracy to force a favorable labor settlement or the 
sale of the newspaper 
the new complaint claims the unions violated the 
labormanagement relations act which prohibits unions from 
interfering with the business of parties not involved in a labor 
dispute 
the defendants and agents acting on their behalf have mounted 
a campaign of violence and intimidation against the news dealers 
and advertisers in an effort to disrupt the publication and sale of 
the newspaper the lawsuit said 
the lawsuit asks for more than 50 million in losses that the 
news claims it incurred as a result of the campaign which it said 
included many hundreds of incidents of arson assault 
vandalism threats and harassment 
theodore kheel a labor attorney and adviser to the unions 
denied the allegations he cited recent testimony by senior police 
officials who said investigations found the violence was committed 
by individuals and was not part of a coordinated conspiracy 
kheel said the news lawsuits against the unions constituted 
harassment 
the news has published every day during the strike but the 
majority of the citys 12000 newsstands and vendors have stopped 
selling the paper and major advertisers have pulled their accounts 
before the strike it was the nations thirdlargest 
metropolitan daily with circulation of 109 million circulation 
has dropped to about 600000 
