an appeals court has dismissed a libel case 
against san francisco chronicle columnist herb caen saying his 
item about a deputy sheriffs arrest on violence and drug charges 
was not libelous because it was true 
the state court of appeal on dec 18 dismissed the libel suit by 
former san francisco sheriffs deputy robert heimbaugh 
caen wrote in january 1987 that heimbaugh had been booked at 
city jail on charges of brandishing a gun beating his livein lady 
friend and possessing drug paraphernalia the district attorneys 
office wants to prosecute but is in a quandary because the 
allegedly battered nonbride will not testify against him heimbaugh 
is out on bail and on medical leave 
the appeals court said the deputy had indeed been arrested 10 
days before the column appeared on charges of corporal punishment 
of a cohabitant brandishing a weapon and possession of narcotics 
paraphernalia 
therefore the lawsuit was without merit the court ruled the 
charges against heimbaugh were later dropped 
caen has written a daily shortitem column featuring gossip 
jokes and tales about san francisco and its people for 52 years in 
a footnote the court characterized caen as the journalistic 
equivalent of the golden gate bridge 
heimbaugh did not dispute the facts in the item but argued that 
the column was untrue because the charges were later dropped and 
his bail was canceled the court ruled that those developments did 
not make the published item libelous 
heimbaugh resigned from the sheriffs department and works as a 
cab driver and bartender in san francisco he also has worked as a 
legal researcher 
he said that although he had not yet seen the courts opinion he 
intended to appeal 
</TEXT>
