<DOCNO> AP901224-0135 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
marychapin carpenter writes true stories 
her characters are single women like herself theyre breaking 
up with a boyfriend or maybe just thinking about one from long ago 
they like to dance and they like quiet moments just talking on the 
phone with a close friend 
she named her second album state of the heart and the songs 
lived up to it a roulette wheel of emotions from lust to regret 
shooting straight in the dark is her new record but carpenter 
thinks human behavior might have worked better as a title 
a lot of the tunes are about human behavior kneejerk 
reactions to certain things carpenter said during an interview 
many are about me not so much about me but about feelings that i 
have and observations in people i know 
if id actually have to choose id have to say i like 
nonfiction more than fiction she said i like biographies 
im a history buff ive never been able to get into science 
fiction or fantasy i like things that are real 
carpenter tells of women frightened by love and frightened of 
being alone sometimes they get angry in the more things 
change a woman hears an old boyfriend is running round town and 
cant help remarking only the names have changed 
other times they let go down at the twist and shout is an 
oldfashioned saturday night dance song a release from all that 
tension in going out tonight the woman is by herself but 
not for long she has empty arms and perfume on her wrist when she 
leaves her apartment her meddling heart will stay behind 
shes basically saying ive had enough of this mourning 
its almost a mercenary kind of thing shes going out of spite 
carpenter said 
thats the one song that was cowritten with coproducer 
john jennings we really went at each other from a malefemale kind 
of thing he came with what i thought were male ways of looking at 
it and i had a female way of looking at it 
musically carpenter mixes country folk and rock n roll the 
lyrics are simple conversational like excerpts from a diary 
there are no metaphors or any other devices to draw attention to 
the writer precise details the color of a shirt are what 
matter just taking a series of facts and emotions and shaping them 
into a story 
i personally feel the best satisfaction i can get after 
working on a tune is using the most succinct language concrete 
images not being too obtuse i dont like too many farflung 
images i just wanted to be as accurate and direct as possible 
she said 
with some writers i want to pull that curtain away ive 
always been more drawn to writers who are concrete people like guy 
clark i also like bruce cockburn hes a very literate direct 
writer 
carpenter was born in princeton nj but spent most of her 
childhood in washington dc she listened to her sisters beatles 
and motown records and by age 9 was playing guitar and scribbling 
down poems 
she was 19 when she first started performing appearing on open 
mike nights at a local bar after graduating from brown university 
she continued playing at bars in washington and eventually gathered 
enough material to make a demo 
columbia records signed her and her debut album hometown 
girl came out in 1987 state of the heart was released last 
year 
fame has brushed against her and quickly sped away on her first 
record she covered tom waits downtown train and was surprised 
to hear it in a washington mall last year she was listening to rod 
stewarts hit version 
in 1988 she wrote the sexy read my lips and to her horror 
the same phrase became george bushs campaign theme for not raising 
taxes the promise of carpenters words has held up longer 
but her own name may soon be good enough state of the heart 
produced four hits on the country charts and you win again is a 
hit off the new album she also received a standing ovation at this 
years country music association awards ceremony for the not so 
tongueincheek opening act 
the moon and st christopher off her new album is her most 
personal song a story so true it almost frightened her off the 
character can only be carpenter and shes pouring a lifetime of 
confessions into 4 minutes and 21 seconds 
i pray for the heart and nerve she sings she kicks herself 
for being such a stubborn woman in such stubborn times she 
regrets the times she ran from lovers and friends 
if her other songs are bulletins from the front updates on 
women seeking middle ground then the moon and st christopher 
is a prayer that all the battles are worth fighting a moment of 
reflection before picking herself up and giving the world another 
chance 
the tune basically happened because a friend of mine had some 
news that changed his life and kind of changedmine those things 
force you to examine who you are why you ended up the way you are 
what your failures were she said 
i feel kind of exposed by that song and its very scary in a 
way but its also about the most satisfying thing i wrote because 
i really got down to the nittygritty people tend to come up to 
you and tell you they got it they related to it it makes me think 
the more personal it is the more universal 
</TEXT>
