<TEXT>
to some the welfare systems in northern europe 
are the worlds most humane to others theyre a wasteful gravy 
train supporting thousands of people who could work if they had 
to now an economic downturn is threatening the generous systems 
and some people living off them will feel the pinch 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some of northern europes welfare 
states wonder how to keep their cradletograve safety nets from 
fraying in the impending recession 
in the postworld war ii boom years the scandinavian countries 
the netherlands and west germany introduced programs that spend up 
to a quarter of the gross national product on welfare 
welfare spending now is outstripping the industrial growth that 
was supposed to pay the bill with growth slowing in many european 
countries some governments are considering cutbacks 
with less money available for welfare government officials 
complain more loudly about people abusing the system 
dutch prime minister ruud lubbers says his nations welfare 
system which will cost the government 1323 billion guilders 
796 billion in 1991 is out of hand 
in a recent report the organization for economic cooperation 
and development citing hollands high income taxes and generous 
welfare benefits concluded that incentives to work are low the 
nation has an 11 percent unemployment rate 
dutch authorities recently failed to lure jobless amsterdam 
residents to the understaffed flower industry even after the 
government offered a car for every four workers to use for 
commuting as well as personal use 
denmark spends 40 percent of its budget on the 14 million 
people 28 percent of the population who live on welfare the 
centerright coalition government of prime minister poul schlueter 
hopes it can reduce welfare dependency by stimulating private 
industry 
denmark has 20000 people under 40 years of age getting 
permanent government pensions of 3709 kroner 662 a month 
because of drug or alcohol problems 
in europe welfare helps the employed as well as the jobless 
the system commonly includes free medical insurance sick pay 
disability and old age pensions and childcare and unemployment 
benefits 
in sweden parents can qualify for benefits for taking time off 
to nurse a sick child 
the basic thing is that everyone should have basic 
opportunities to take part in all activities within our 
society said annchristen filipson of the swedish social affairs 
ministry 
scandinavian taxpayers can hardly be expected to dig deeper in 
their pockets to pay a greater share of the welfare costs their 
tax rates of more than 50 percent already are highest in the 
industrialized world 
last october swedens ruling social democratic party made the 
first cuts ever in a social welfare system now costing 25139 
billion kronor 4513 billion just over onefifth of the gnp 
the government is expected to cut 15 billion kronor 269 
billion dollars from the welfare budget in 1991 the government is 
also planning to cut sick pay rates from 100 percent to 75 percent 
of a workers salary for the first three days in an effort to 
discourage malingering workers take an average 25 days of sick 
leave a year 
the welfare programs are usually funded by taxes paid by 
employers and employees and some are getting fed up 
ove danemar of the swedish employers federation criticized 
the whole system because it stimulates people to work less 
and to take more leisure time 
the private sector cant bear it any longer he said its 
no longer consistent with a modern economy 
critics say many of the benefits were begun in good faith but 
have ended up being abused during more favorable economic times 
the abuse was widely tolerated but with the continent entering a 
recession there is more clamping down on wasteful spending 
lubbers has vowed to curb hollands unsuitability for work act 
under which nearly 900000 people get lifelong disability pensions 
of up to 70 percent of their lastearned pay in the late 1970s 
some companies used it by dismissing unproductive employees 
passing the social cost on to the government 
about onethird of the programs beneficiaries claim 
psychological reasons for being unable to work in a recent speech 
lubbers said wryly looking at the statistics one has to 
admit that ours is a sick nation 
this spring the dutch government is expected to make deep cuts 
in the housing education and cultural subsidies that complement 
the welfare handouts themselves equal to at least 70 percent of 
the minimum wage it has borrowed heavily and diverted money from 
other programs to cover welfare costs 
only germany is making large welfare increases to pay millions 
of former east germans who are unemployed 
norway is slightly expanding its 1258 billion kroner 21 
billion welfare system on which almost a quarter of the 
population depends in some form or other the labor government has 
added about one billion kroner 166 million to the bill since 
coming into office last month and even the rightleaning opposition 
progress party favors the expansion 
