<TEXT>
for three years the tobacco lobby has worked 
hard to influence an environmental protection agency report on the 
risks tobacco smoke poses to nonsmokers using the freedom of 
information act the associated press obtained documents that 
reveal details of this classic confrontation between science and 
big business 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when the environmental protection agency 
convened a panel of scientific experts to rule on whether 
secondhand cigarette smoke causes lung cancer in nonsmokers both 
sides arrived fully armed 
most of the megatonnage belonged to the tobacco industry which 
employed an army of public relations people brandishing bulging 
reports ebutting everything ever said about the dangers of passive 
smoking 
antismoking scientists and activists unable to match the 
industrys fire power relied on carefully timed press releases and 
other surgical strikes 
but this gathering in arlington on dec 45 was just the latest 
most visible battle in a war that had gone on quietly in epa 
offices and lawyers conference rooms for three years 
correspondence and memorandums obtained by the associated press 
under the freedom of information act reveal strenuous efforts by 
the tobacco industry to influence the epa deliberations on 
secondhand smoke 
the stakes were obvious and enormous 
if secondhand smoke is officially listed as a class a 
carcinogen a known cause of human cancer it is the end of 
smoking in any public place said julia carol of americans for 
nonsmokers rights in berkeley calif 
certainly this was an important issue to us said brennan 
dawson a spokeswoman for the tobacco institute the industrys 
trade group in washington dc what we have tried to do is stay 
in the process 
the industry has proven adept at that it has not only been with 
the process but ahead of it 
in october 1987 industry lawyers met with robert axelrad 
director of the epas indoor air division before the epas study 
of passive smoke and cancer had even begun 
they were correctly guessing we might get into tobacco 
smoke said axelrad it was a get acquainted 
in a march 18 1988 letter to the epa samuel chilcote 
president of the tobacco institute laid out the industrys 
position the evidence doesnt show tobacco smoke causes lung 
cancer in nonsmokers 
two years earlier both the us surgeon general and the 
national research council had concluded that passive smoking does 
cause lung cancer the tobacco industry didnt accept the 
conclusions of either report 
chilcote went so far as to suggest the phrasing the epa ought to 
use he warned against the terms passive smoking and 
involuntary smoking 
they could cause confusion and lead to a mistaken view that 
exposure to ets environmental tobacco smoke is in fact 
involuntary smoking chilcote wrote these terms should 
simply be avoided 
the industry also argued that ventilation not restriction of 
smoking is the best way to clear the air 
the epas position is that all indoor air pollutants including 
cigarette smoke are best removed by elimination of the source not 
by ventilation 
the epa said so in letters to the tobacco institute and its 
lawyers the industry repeated its assertions again and again for 
two years 
by june 1989 william rosenberg the epas assistant 
administrator for air and radiation had had enough in a letter to 
a tobacco industry lawyer he criticized the industrys insistence 
that the evidence linking passive smoking to cancer is 
controversial 
the fact of the matter is we find the surgeon general and the 
national research council reports to be highly credible 
rosenberg wrote 
frankly the tobacco industrys argument would be more 
credible if it were not so similar to the tobacco industrys 
position on direct smoking despite the estimated 50000 studies 
linking smoking with disease in humans 
the tempo of the exchange between the epa and the industry 
picked up last june a draft copy of the epa report was leaked and 
then officially released to the press unflinchingly it concluded 
that secondhand smoke is a known cause of lung cancer 
the industry stepped up its lobbying when the epa appointed the 
panel of scientific experts that would meet in arlington the 
industry worked ard for the dismissal of dr david burns the 
senior editor of the surgeon generals report on passive smoking 
the effort succeeded but not for long when word of his 
dismissal got out burns was reappointed 
us rep thomas bliley of richmond va where philip morris 
is the largest private employer took up the industry cause 
he wrote to the epa to say that the reappointment of burns 
raises serious questions about the overall integrity of the 
selection process 
the charge was that burns was an activist and therefore 
couldnt be impartial burns denied the charge and many other 
scientists said he was one of the nations leading authorities on 
the subject of passive smoking 
subsequent news reports revealed that six of the 16 scientists 
on the panel had ties to a tobacco industry research organization 
one of the six was also negotiating for a 12 million research 
grant from philip morris while serving on the epa panel a seventh 
was recommended by the tobacco industry 
the loudest outcry over those revelations didnt come from 
antismoking activists it came from bliley the industry ally 
the selection process has become so deeply enmeshed in 
political and media controversy that an objective review by the 
present panel is no longer possible he wrote on nov 23 he 
urged the epa to select a new expert panel a move that would have 
delayed completion of the final epa report 
the entire process has drawn criticism from all sides its 
not the first time the industry has tried to influence science 
said dr alan blum the founder of doctors ought to care an 
antismoking group 
he said he was puzzled by the publics apparent lack of concern 
if the toxic waste people tried to do something like this they 
would be blasted by everyone in the country when the tobacco 
industry does it we look at it as business as usual 
dawson of the tobacco institute blamed the disruption of the 
scientific process on antismoking advocates there has been a 
lot of involvement by the antismoking community that we dont 
think should be there she said if youre going to pursue 
science it ought to be without advocacy 
we dont have lobbyists everywhere protested carol at 
americans for nonsmokers rights we have not felt that it was 
our business to tell the epa what the science is 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP901224-0160 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
not long after a good friend died fighting 
members of a rival gang the nightmares began for nightowl 
the gang member who says he fears police reprisal if he gives 
his real name dreams that he is bound hand and foot the man who 
killed his friend chopper six months ago points a gun at him and 
fires 
i can see him and im scared and im full of hate nightowl 
says then i wake up and i think i cant go down to the 
neighborhood because if i do im going to die but you know i go 
down anyway 
nightowl his street name is dressed in typical gang fashion 
white tshirt and oversized pants his hair is closecropped except 
at the nape of the neck where it is tied in a small ponytail 
the 19yearold is a member of the clarence street locos three 
locos have been killed so far this year in the gangs war with the 
rival east la dukes and the locos say theres no truce in sight 
its never going to stop too many have died already said a 
member of the mafia connection an ally of the locos 
bloody warfare among black and hispanic street gangs has made 
1990 a record year for gangrelated homicides in the nations 
secondlargest city 
gang killings are up a staggering 53 percent in suburban areas 
patrolled by los angeles county sheriffs deputies the gang death 
count was at 160 as of nov 30 compared to 104 during the same 
period in 1989 and 116 gang murders for all of 1989 
in the city of los angeles there was a 124 percent jump in 
gang killings as of nov 30 with 315 dead in 1989 276 people 
were killed in gangrelated incidents during that period with a 
total of 303 gang homicides committed for all of 1989 
cmdr william booth said the numbers are deceptive because 
police today can better identify gang members and investigators 
are more likely to call a murder gangrelated than they were in the 
past even so gang violence is increasing he said 
they have the weapons and they have the mobility plus they 
simply have little reverence for human life somebody elses 
life booth said its almost an animal kind of syndrome that 
prevails with the gang mentality 
the stories behind the statistics illustrate the heartbreak and 
terror of gang violence 
a 5yearold south los angeles girl was killed by a stray 
bullet as she joined friends to sing happy birthday at a party 
in eastern los angeles county albert domingo simenia 36 was 
fatally stabbed while battling eight gang members in his front 
yard 
in suburban la puente worried school officials canceled a 
high school football game following 16 gangrelated shootings in 
two weeks 
fourteen people including two toddlers were wounded in a 
nov 30 driveby attack during a family party in valinda 
the carnage has overshadowed the success of an antigang pilot 
program in a south los angeles area controlled by the crips and 
bloods two predominantly black gangs 
the violence is not even personal said the rev gregory 
boyle a roman catholic priest who has buried 10 gang members this 
year from his east los angeles parish the war were having right 
now there are even brothers flesh and blood brothers on 
different sides 
police most often blame the increased violence on easytoget 
weapons and the release of hundreds of older latino gang members 
imprisoned since the mid1980s 
youth workers however say an influx of central american 
immigrants has changed the nature of hispanic gangs traditional 
neighborhood gangs that fought over neighborhood boundaries are 
giving way to more pragmatic groups trafficking in drugs and 
prostitution said steve valdivia director of community youth gang 
services 
in the latino community the warriors have changed but the 
war goes on valdivia said 
it has a direct correlation with the political and economic 
upheaval in other countries a lot of them come over with a violent 
history the law enforcement here is no match for what they saw 
over there over there the police cut off an arm or slit your 
throat here they put you in jail and feed you well he said 
but others argue that police have been too heavyhanded in 
dealing with gangs as the violence increases so has the criticism 
of the rough shakedowns and neighborhood sweeps that have been law 
enforcements primary tool 
police themselves are saying that social programs are needed to 
turn youths away from gangs 
were arresting more people were prosecuting more people 
said sheriff sherman block the problem is the law enforcement 
workload continues to grow because of failures in other 
institutions were talking about school dropout rates alternative 
programs that will offer the same kind of need satisfaction that 
the gangs offer 
of the estimated 100000 gang members in los angeles county 5 
percent to 8 percent are hopetodie killercriminals who 
should be in jail valdivia said the rest he said probably can 
be turned away from gangs if they realize there is an alternative 
the same things work in any community those are prevention 
mobilization community action and law enforcement opportunity is 
a nice thing to throw in also he said youd be surprised how 
people behave when you treat them as human beings 
valdivia said a onetwo punch of tough law enforcement and 
social programs reduced violence in two south los angeles 
neighborhoods which until last year had been the nations worst 
for gang violence 
while police confronted gang members in the streets youth gang 
services organized basketball and softball leagues and offered 
classes to teach young people how to prepare for job interviews 
parttime jobs were offered through the department of public works 
as a result the southeast precinct reported just 17 
gangrelated homicides during the first eight months of 1990 
compared to 39 the previous year in the 77th precinct 
gangrelated killings dropped from 42 to 27 according to police 
statistics 
folks will tell you theres a different feeling said 
charles norman youth services director in the southeast precinct 
if we can do this the negative element is just going to move 
on 
norman said some youths joined gangs to avoid becoming their 
prey 
take away the jungle atmosphere most kids wont join a gang 
they dont need it he said 
but for those already in a gang loyalties run deep nightowl 
said police crackdowns just make them deeper 
he said authorities would stand a better chance of staunching 
the bloodshed by providing educational opportunities and jobs 
like most of the locos nightowl is a high school dropout 
steady jobs are hard to find 
the teenager whose father also was a gang member soon will 
become a father himself the cycle he said is tough to break 
you know what scares me most is the thought that my little 
kid is going to grow up and be a gang member he said it 
scares the hell out of me but you know what can you do about 
it 
</TEXT>
