<TEXT>
in a neighborhood numbed by murderous gang 
warfare the rev gregory boyle battles the violence with what he 
considers the voice of reason and the love of god 
since arriving at the dolores mission five years ago boyle has 
persuaded mothers to take guns away from their gangmember sons and 
coaxed dozens of gang members to attend the missions alternative 
high school 
but in gaining the trust of young gangsters boyle has roused 
the suspicion of police who say his openarms approach gives the 
gangs legitimacy they dont deserve 
boyle in turn has become a sharp critic of antigang 
strategies that rely on force and intimidation 
the image for me always is symptom vs problem said boyle 
the police dont have a clue to what the problem is so what hope 
do we have that they will be part of the solution the problem is 
dysfunctional families and poverty and boredom and jobs you 
address that and the gang mess will dry up 
a los angeles native boyle 36 was ordained to the jesuit 
order in 1984 after graduating from the weston school of theology 
in boston he spent the next year working in an impoverished 
village in the bolivian highlands where he was converted to 
religious activism 
when boyle arrived at dolores he began searching for a solution 
to the bloody warfare waged by 11 gangs that operate in the parish 
soon he decided he could accomplish more by working with the gangs 
instead of against them 
it is a strategy police dislike capt bob medina commander of 
the los angeles police departments hollenbeck division said boyle 
has undermined police efforts to convince young people that gang 
membership in itself is bad 
he permits them to congregate over there to wear their 
colors i think thats contrary to what were trying to do 
medina said were trying to dissuade youngsters from joining 
gangs the actions he has taken gives them some credibility and 
makes them proud to be in gangs 
boyle turned dolores mission a parish church and school about 
two miles east of downtown los angeles into a sort of nomans 
land where gang members are welcome to congregate provided they 
leave weapons drugs and liquor outside 
boyle acknowleded his strategy hasnt stopped the killing so 
far this year he has buried 10 gang members and attended services 
for even more 
but he points out that more than a decade of aggressive police 
crackdowns has failed to stem a steady increase in violence 
during 1990 gang killings have increased more than 30 percent 
in the hollenbeck division which includes boyles parish 
according to police statistics overall gangrelated violence in 
the area is up more than 50 percent 
boyle blames the carnage on poverty and despair in his parish 
a mostly hispanic area of public housing projects and aging 
woodframe houses jobs are scarce and teens frequently drop out of 
high school long before graduation 
its all despair so threats of any kind all those things 
that would work in someone who cared it doesnt cut it for kids 
who dont have a sense of hope for a better future boyle said 
earlier this year medina asked boyles superiors in san 
francisco to transfer the priest out of east los angeles church 
officials declined medina said since then archbishop roger 
mahony in los angeles has reaffirmed his support for boyles 
campaign 
boyle said that so far he has been unable to achieve one of his 
major goals to arrange a lasting ceasefire among warring gangs 
but at times his approach pays off 
last summer boyle found temporary jobs for about 40 gang 
members so long as they were working they refrained from 
gangbangings or launching attacks on rival bands he said 
several gang members interviewed in the missions small 
recreation room said there was less temptation to fight when they 
were employed 
when you get a job you change because youre making money you 
can go places you dont have to stay around here said one gang 
member who refused to give his name you dont have to steal you 
dont have to sell dope you got a job it does change a lot of 
people 
boyle said he believes his approach despising the sin but not 
the sinner will work in the long run but that is not why he 
employs it 
the stand this church has to gang members is what jesus would 
do that its morally correct and based on the gospel he said 
to work with them and find jobs for them and lovingly accept them 
is what jesus would do whether any of that works is not my 
concern i think it works but thats not the point 
</TEXT>
