<TEXT>
he may seem quite mad but he is carefully assessing this baby 
measuring attention span independence good humor energy level 
he will see 150 babies a day cut the lot to some 30 three will 
eventually be chosen the star and two standins 
he meets one mother in the waiting room she hands the baby over 
to him and the baby cries he hands the baby back says the baby is 
lovely but a little nervous today the mother cries 
she knows its over and she wanted another try hicks says 
i was trying to be real nice and you have to try to explain that 
if i brought the baby into the audition room id only be appeasing 
them i know they have unrealistic expectations they drove a long 
way and i feel bad for them 
one of the toughest things we have to do is to hand a baby 
over to an actor or an actress hicks adds in an audition all 
i have to do is get a baby to perform and they can do some pretty 
amazing things but when i have to hand that baby to an actor or an 
actress ive lost control and its unnerving 
an actor may be able to fool the creative execs but he cant 
fool the baby the baby can tell by the touch its instinctual 
and the kid will scream its the best alarm system for bad acting 
youll ever find 
hicks remembers one commercial involving three babies in 
costume one of whom kept falling asleep then someone got the 
bright idea of putting a pair of sunglasses on the dozing child and 
it actually added to the commercials charm 
one of the toughest commercials we did was with a tire covered 
with a blanket rogers says 
they wanted a baby to walk up to the covered tire stand there a 
couple of seconds and then whip off the blanket and they wanted 
to shoot it in one take when you want a baby to do something 
thats what they wont do rogers says we couldnt get a baby 
to do it theyd walk in take a few steps then crawl and crawl 
right past the tire 
finally on one of the last shots of the day one of the babies 
did it perfectly 
one commercial will linger in mike rogers memory forever 
