<TEXT>
ragged glory reprise neil young and crazy horse 
 
neil young continues to change musical personae more often than 
most guitarists change strings 
youngs 25album catalog includes country rockabilly synthpop 
and some of the most beautiful ballads of his generation but 
ragged glory as the title would suggest is an hour of rock 
n roll as only young can play it 
paired with crazy horse a threepiece band that has 
intermittently backed him since 1969 young delivers a raw 
scorching set dominated by guitar solos 
he draws from an immense vocabulary of riffs built up over two 
decades the fretboard workout includes crunching chords ringing 
melodies bent notes and feedback occasionally the energy flags 
when a break runs a little long four of the 10 songs clock in at 
more than seven minutes but youngs playing never sounds 
methodical 
the garageband sound is matched with lyrics that have this 
child of the 60s sounding nostalgic theres a mansion on the 
hill young sings psychedelic music fills the air peace and 
love live there still theres a mansion on the hill 
even when waxing sentimental young sings with the energy of a 
teenager his casual relationship with the proper key is 
dylanesque and he doesnt think twice about roaming an octave 
above his range 
ragged glory is a stark contrast to youngs marvelous 1989 
album freedom which contains angry more polished music but 
if you need a guitar fix this neils for you 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
