<TEXT>
the secret is out and remember that you heard it 
here first arlo guthrie never really wanted to be a folk singer 
forget for a moment that hes the son of woody guthrie who 
wrote more than 1000 songs or that hes written a sizable number 
of memorable tunes himself forget all those great interpretations 
of goodnight irene amazing grace stealin and this 
land is your land that youve heard him do over the years dont 
even think about alices restaurant that epic tale of youthful 
rebellion and antiwar protest 
what arlo guthrie really wanted to be was a newspaper reporter 
yeah there must be a repressed reporter in one of my hidden 
personalities because i love to write laughs guthrie whose 
musical career has seen him evolve from the 60skid protest singer 
with a sense of humor to one of the preeminent voices in american 
folk music 
but he says i didnt become a folk singer because i wanted to 
be i ended up doing this because i didnt know how to do anything 
else 
and that hasnt changed much he adds with that quick 
goodnatured laugh that his fans have heard so often over the 
years its the one that sometimes surfaces right on stage in the 
middle of a song when something strikes him so funny that he has 
to stop and tell everyone about it 
but now the funny stories the wry asides the general 
observations on the oddities of life are as apt to go down on paper 
as over a microphone in a concert hall 
the ones that are written go into guthries newsletter the 
rolling blunder review an espistle written in a style that evokes 
rollicking images of the kind of oldtime journalism chronicled in 
such movies as the front page 
but the newsletter never started out to be a newsletter 
it sort of came about by accident guthrie says 
in the mid70s he began collecting addresses of people who 
might want a schedule of his shows but he never really got around 
to sending them one 
people started asking us when are you going to send us 
something theyd say i signed up 14 times and i never got 
anything he recalled 
so with a great sense of guilt the rolling blunder review was 
born guthrie and his wife jackie typed it on a single sheet of 
paper made copies and mailed it from their home in washington 
mass early issues contained only the longsought schedule and a 
few funny comments on alices restaurant and other songs 
but as word spread the newsletter grew five years later its 
an eightpage quarterly containing stories letters to the editor 
and information on how to buy guthries albums tshirts and other 
merchandise theres even a cooking column by alice brock you 
remember alice theres a song about alice 
some 60000 to 70000 people pay 3 a year for it although it 
goes free to people in hospitals and prisons 
among the stories in recent issues are reports on concerts to 
benefit the environment and in support of student protests in china 
and elsewhere but somehow almost everything no matter how 
serious comes out funny sort of like an arlo guthrie concert 
he notes that one role of a folk singer is to comment on 
political events of the day as his father pete seeger joan baez 
and so many others have done 
but its not the only job and it may not even be the most 
important job he said the most important thing for me 
personally is maintaining a sense of humor in an oftenhumorless 
world 
for guthrie the laughs have been frequent only he for 
example could show us in alices restaurant how to use a 
litterbug arrest as a reason to stay out of the army during the 
vietnam war only he has dared speculate in the pause of mr 
claus that santa claus might enter houses late at night because 
hes a dope fiend or that a delightful folk ditty about the joys 
of tilling the earth the garden song should be played 
backward in search of evil messages 
the laughs have been so frequent that theyve allowed some to 
overlook the musical talent guthrie is more than proficient on 
guitar piano harmonica and banjo as well as a singer of some 
range and a writer whose best songs evoke strong images of joy and 
sometimes sorrow 
alices restaurant started it all in 1967 making him an 
overnight star at age 20 
who could have ever imagined it he says of the way the 
youth culture embraced his 18minute guitaraccompanied monologue 
on how he used a thanksgiving day arrest to stay out of the army 
the song also helped him escape early comparisons with a legendary 
father 
and although guthrie has almost always included a woody guthrie 
song or two in his concert repertoire he downplays the fatherson 
connection 
for whatever cosmic reasons and who really understands those 
things i ended up similar to my dad in some ways he says 
but were vastly different in other ways 
but the connection also brings up another inevitable question 
woody guthrie died in 1967 of the debilitating neurological 
disorder huntingtons chorea it has a 5050 chance of being passed 
from parent to child it strikes in middle age and arlo guthrie is 
43 
but he dismisses such inquiries goodnaturedly im not dead 
yet he says does that answer your question 
he is also not through working yet continuing to tour regularly 
and making plans to record again after several years without a new 
album 
ive written some new songs he says ive got enough for 
a totally new record 
hes also thinking about an animated version for children of 
alices restaurant which was made into a movie in 1969 
it would focus more on the thanksgiving part and less on the 
littering and draft parts he says 
he notes that the idea of dumping a half a ton of garbage by 
the side of the road isnt as popular as it once was even if the 
dump was closed on thanksgiving and youd never heard of a dump 
closed on thanksgiving before 
littering isnt such a good idea anymore he says a bit 
sheepishly but then he adds with that quick laugh i sure had a 
lot of fun on that day though 
</TEXT>
