<TEXT>
from the weakened bank of new england to the 
neighborhood savings bank experts say the regions financial 
institutions are limping into a recession they helped cause 
the economic slowdown sweeping new england is part cyclical but 
bankers and economists say it also reflects the extraordinary 
overoptimism displayed by lenders in the booming 1980s optimism 
rivaled only by that of the southwests savings and loan managers 
bankers are just scared stiff that they are in a texasstyle 
freefall that could envelop all the regions banks said paul 
getman an analyst with regional financial associates a banking 
consultant based in westchester pa 
this is a bankingled recession theres no question about 
that getman said that is why it is particularly bad in the 
new england area and why that area is the worst in the nation 
new englands economy is far more diverse and able to absorb a 
slump than was the oilbased economy of texas in the 1980s and 
strict zoning laws in new england acted as a brake on 
overdevelopment texas had no such restrictions and left itself 
wideopen for the inevitable bust following the boom 
every major bank holding company in texas essentially 
failed said ken guenther of the independent bankers association 
of america a washingtonbased banking association thats not 
going to happen in new england but there wont be a light at the 
end of the tunnel until real estate values stabilize 
statistics generated by the federal deposit insurance corp bear 
out the weakened condition of banking in new england 
massachuesetts connecticut new hampshire and maine were among 
the top six states in terms of commercial bank losses in the first 
three quarters of the year 
the fdic reported that there is little prospect of nearterm 
improvement in the northeast 
in a sign that banks expect times to get leaner the 180 
commercial banks in massachusetts rhode island and connecticut 
sharply increased their reserves for bad loans this year 
savings banks which were once limited to smallscale loans 
much like the savings and loan institutions dominate new england 
banking and they too are in trouble threequarters of the 
nations 471 savings banks are in new england 
a recent house banking subcommittee report referred to severe 
weakness among savings banks and to earnings that had 
nosedived 
even some bankers admit that lending practices by their 
colleagues contributed to the economic slide 
i believe that it was an overextension of credit in commercial 
real estate said jasper j jaser president of prime bank in 
orange conn banks were lending against equity which did not 
exist said jaser who is also chairman of connecticuts 
independent bankers association 
the situation in connecticut jaser said is still in a state 
of deterioration he predicted that several banks would close 
or be swallowed up by larger banks 
the nations banking community is closely watching the bank of 
new england which is based in boston and also owns connecticuts 
largest bank connecticut bank and trust 
not one banker wants to see bank of new england fail because 
it will cast a pall over all of them said getman of regional 
financial associates 
anticipating a possible spate of closures the fdic has opened a 
field office in franklin mass with 350 employees ready to handle 
the work that goes along with a bank failure 
not everyone blames the banks for causing the economic downturn 
lawmakers from the region have been harshly critical of what they 
call excessive federal regulation of new england banks others have 
blamed overly restrictive laws 
michael devito of the rhode island bankers association said 
federal tax reform in 1986 made real estate a less attractive 
investment and contributed to the downturn in new england where 
real estate is an important part of the economy in addition 
devito said the 1980s saw the growth of investment firms that 
could offer mutual funds and compete with banks for depositors 
dollars 
but state and federal officials may be in no mood to ease 
restrictions on banking as devito advocates if anything the 
pressure may be in the opposite direction according to jaser 
prime banks president the errors of banks over the past several 
years may lead to reforms that more strictly control lending 
i dont believe this is going to be looked at in the future as 
a cyclical situation jaser said i believe there are going to 
be some serious ramifications 
</TEXT>
