<TEXT>
karl h hinke a longtime banking 
executive who created the mastercard credit card has died at age 
84 
hinke the former chairman of the interbank card association and 
a retired executive of marine midland bank where he worked for 55 
years died saturday at his home in east aurora outside buffalo 
mastercard was started in 1966 as a competitor to the card 
issued by bank of america after that bank which was licensing 
other banks to issue its card refused marine midland a license 
because marine was too big 
hinke then executive vice president of the buffalobased marine 
midland persuaded marine to start a credit card association in 
competition with bank of america 
the trial credit card operation was started in binghamton and 
spread to jamestown syracuse rochester and buffalo it then 
attracted other east coast banks including chase manhattan mellon 
bank and the bank of detroit which formed the interbank card 
association in 1966 
by the end of 1967 there were 150 members and interbank 
eventually overtook bank of america which consolidated its efforts 
and became a member of interbank its credit card originally was 
named master charge and later was renamed mastercard 
earlier in his career with marine midland hinke brought the 
bank into the business of financing accounts receivable and 
inventory for companies unable to obtain unsecured financing a 
novel idea in banking when hinke proposed it in the late 1930s 
hinke a world war ii veteran of the marine corps retired from 
marine midlands board of directors in 1971 and from the marine 
advisory council a group of former marine directors in 1982 
he is survived by donne his wife of 43 years and a son 
frederick william of leesburg va services will be private 
 
</TEXT>
