<TEXT>
the us dollar is rapidly becoming the currency 
of choice in the soviet union due to growing confusion over the 
value of the ruble during the countrys struggle to become a 
marketdriven economy 
rubles are worth nothing outside the soviet union because the 
government refuses to back them with hard currency gold or silver 
but inside the country tourists can walk up to a moscow hotel 
currency booth and buy six rubles for one dollar or 16 cents each 
if they use a credit card they get 18 rubles for that same 
dollar the socalled commercial rate 
on the black market a dollar fetches about 20 rubles 
confusion reigns everywhere said andy rafalat deputy 
general director of moscows two pizza hut restaurants 
more and more firms have been switching as many transactions as 
possible to hard currencies the favorite being the us dollar 
leaders of the huge russian republic who want to make the ruble 
the only legal currency in the country have coined a word for the 
trend dollarization 
barter deals from pepsicos vodkaforoil tankers deal to 
using the instantly recognizable redandwhite marlboro cigarette 
package to flag a cab are also becoming more popular 
until recently foreign businesses had dealt in the official or 
hard ruble known in russian as valuta their price tags and 
restaurant menus were printed in official rubles but payable only 
in hard currency or credit cards at the official rate 
this rate was effectively replaced in november with a new 
commercial exchange rate devaluing the ruble to 18 rubles to the 
dollar from 16 rubles 
in his decree president mikhail s gorbachev indicated this 
rate was to cover all international commercial transactions by 
soviet companies as well as joint ventures with foreign firms and 
foreign residents in the soviet union 
the official rate was retained only for international currency 
comparisons and to protect third world countries whose debts are in 
rubles 
finland the soviet unions closest western trading partner was 
so confused that its central bank stopped clearing ruble 
transactions for nearly one week 
in moscow the swisssoviet joint venture sadko kept its staff 
on overtime one night to change all its price tags ruble prices 
were tripled but since the new ruble was worth only onethird of 
the old one the hard currency price remained the same 
pizza hut immediately started writing its credit card bills in 
us dollars to avoid any risk of customers being charged the 
higher exchange rate by banks ignoring the new rules 
explanatory notes have been stapled to all hard currency menus 
and rafalat said the company is considering reprinting them in 
dollars instead of rubles next month to make them easier to 
understand 
we were quite happy to use the hard ruble rate but only if 
theres an acceptable clear definition for our business use which 
at this moment hasnt been the case he said in an interview 
the only 100 percent clear road i can see is by quoting prices 
in another currency as we receive most of our hard currency in 
dollars dollars seem to be the most obvious thing to quote 
stockmann a finnish firm with grocery and department stores in 
moscow kept its price tags in the old official rubles and posted a 
notice on its front door advising customers but on jan 1 it will 
close its two moscow outlets to switch all prices and credit card 
transactions to dollars 
in this confusing situation we find it better to change the 
prices directly to dollars store manager ilkka arvola said 
these continuous questions and explanations between us and our 
customers is completely unnecessary and customers do not like 
this uneasy feeling neither do i he said 
customers sort of think we might be cheating them somehow 
which were not 
switching to dollars should also prevent disruptions the next 
time the ruble rate is changed he said 
western diplomats and businessmen say the new rate is a 
tentative step toward making the ruble convertible as it inches 
the soviet currency closer to its real value 
the soviet government has given no firm indication when or how 
it plans to make the ruble convertible 
</TEXT>
