<TEXT>
rarely has something so green made marketers so 
blue 
in the past year manufacturers have crammed supermarket shelves 
with everything from degradable plastic bags to 
ozonefriendly hair sprays in hopes of cashing in on the 
growing concern about the environment 
but the socalled green revolution one of the most powerful 
marketing machines since oat bran hit the dietary scene is 
grinding its gears lawsuits legislative proposals and consumer 
boycotts have led many companies to stop claiming broad 
environmental benefits for their products 
the major manufacturers have backpedaled because they are 
leery of getting caught in making claims that through no fault of 
their own they cant substantiate said robert mcmath a consumer 
products expert and director of the new products showcase and 
learning center in ithaca ny 
mobil chemical corp said last spring it would refrain from 
promoting its hefty plastic bags as photodegradable after 
consumer and government groups complained the bags wouldnt degrade 
anytime soon inside the darkened recesses of landfills where most 
trash ends up 
seven states subsequently sued mobil this summer saying the 
company hasnt removed all of the existing products that still 
contain those criticized claims 
whats happened is that the hefty incident has really made 
manufacturers go back to square one said simon williams 
president of michael peters design a new york consultant firm that 
specializes in earthfriendly packaging 
retreats from biodegradable claims have since become widespread 
following mobils announcement last spring first brands corp of 
danbury conn and webster industries inc of peabody mass 
said they would also refrain from degradability claims for their 
glad and good sense plastic bags 
american enviro products inc of placentia calif agreed to 
stop promoting its bunnies disposable diapers as biodegradable 
after attorneys general in 10 states threatened to sue 
more recently willamette industries inc of portland ore 
one of the nations largest paper bag manufacturers eliminated the 
words biodegradable and recyclable from the bottom of its 
paper bags distributed at supermarket checkout counters in 17 
western states 
green cross certification co an independent certification firm 
hired by willamette said most consumers will not recycle the 
product and that the bags will take years to degrade in most 
landfills 
willamette still hypes the bags recycled content but green 
cross has verified it is composed of a minimum of 40 percent 
recycled consumer paper 
seventh generation a burlington vtbased mail order firm 
specializing in earthfriendly products announced a new policy 
regarding socalled degradable plastic bags in last springs 
catalog we suspended sale of these bags because we are no longer 
confident they are beneficial to the environment 
large manufacturers feel somewhat caught between the need to 
do something and the fear of figuring out the right thing to do 
while avoiding adverse implications for their current product 
line said jeffrey hollender chairman and chief executive 
officer of seventh generation 
to be fair the green flood has hardly subsided the number of 
new products hyping their ecological soundness nearly tripled this 
year to 751 according to marketing intelligence service ltd a 
research firm in naples ny 
but product consultants say they expect fewer new claims next 
year and they expect more of them to be of the provable kind 
critics say their next area of attack are supposedly 
earthfriendly aerosols whose ozonedestroying chlorofluorocarbons 
have been replaced by other suspect chemicals the biggest new 
growth area are household products ranging from paints to 
cleaners 
weve got to make sure consumers are not going to feel that 
every ad and every bit of labeling is to be disregarded because it 
is false and deceptive said new york state attorney general 
robert abrams in a telephone interview en route from his albany 
office 
indeed state officials praised a recent move by proctor amp 
gamble co to offer wasteefficient refillable containers for 
its downy fabric softener 
early this month at hearings in san diego a group of state 
attorneys general proposed nationwide minimum standards for 
environmental claims consistent with national and state legislation 
currently in draft form 
they also called for reduced use of general hardtodocument 
terms like environmentally friendly instead manufacturers are 
urged to be as detailed as possible when describing claims like 
recycled content telling precisely what percentage of the 
content is recycled 
states including new york connecticut iowa minnesota and 
texas are pressing for legislation that would bar manufacturers 
from using degradable on packages before more research is 
available on just how long it takes these products to decompose a 
new york bill failed to win approval this session 
for the first year there was no guidance said linda brown 
a spokeswoman at green cross which is based in oakland calif 
now companies are taking a closer look to see if any of these 
claims are falling into gray zones 
</TEXT>
